Spending the last year at home has made me all the more aware of the amount of food that goes to waste, so I’m trying to use leftovers in creative ways and prevent as much excess waste as possible. This recipe was born from a fridge raid, I saw what leftovers we had and turned them into these delicious plant based muffins. I used @alpro Greek Style Plain as the base, which is naturally lower in saturated fat and made without added sugars, and I mixed that together with lots of bits from the fridge. You can take the base recipe and adapt it to whatever you have on hand that needs using up. When talking about waste we should also think about recycling and I know I’m not perfect but I’m trying to resuse any plastics we do use as much as possible and then recycle everything we cant, currently the @alpro packaging is 88% plant based and by 2025 it will be 100% recyclable.
-
Makes 6 muffins 
2 vegan eggs (2 tsp psyllium husk (or 2 tbsp ground flax seed) mixed with 6 tbsp water)
200g plain flour
1 tsp salt
3 tsp baking powder
2 tsp fennel seeds
2 tsp smoked paprika
3 vegan sausages, diced
Small handful parsley, finely chopped
Zest of 1 lemon
3 spring onions, sliced 
200ml @alpro Greek style plain
75ml @alpro soya drink
3 tsp chilli oil
Mixed seeds, for topping
-
Whisk together ingredients for vegan egg and set aside until thickened. Mix together flour, salt, baking powder, fennel seeds, paprika, sausages, parsley, lemon zest, spring onionsWhisk together @alpro Greek Style Plain, @alpro soya drink, chilli oil and vegan egg. Pour wet into dry and stir to form a thick batter. Divide between 6 tulip muffin cases (8 regular), sprinkle with seeds and bake at 180c (160c fan) for about 25 mins #goodforyou#plantpower #fridgeraid #theboywhobakes #savourybaking #savourymuffins #veganmuffins #veganbaking #bakersofinstagram

AD as it is currently @cakeweekuk I wanted to do a bakealong for my favourite nostalgic bake, a mash up of two recipes, a classic birthday cake. It’s one bowl vanilla cake and a take on classic fudge frosting. Recipes taken from my book One Tin Bakes. If you fancy winning a copy of the book check out @cakeweekuk’s account as they’re giving one away!
-
INGREDIENTS

One Bowl Vanilla Cake
400g plain flour 
1 1/4 tsp baking powder
2 1/2 tsp bicarbonate of soda 
1 tsp fine sea salt 
400g caster sugar 
3 large eggs 
135ml neutral tasting oil (or light olive)
285ml buttermilk
1 tsp vanilla bean paste 
240ml recently boiled water 

Fudge Frosting
340g unsalted butter 
120g icing sugar 
2 tbsp golden syrup or honey 
60g cocoa powder 
80ml sour cream 
80ml hot water 
200g dark chocolate, melted and cooled
-

#ad Hey guys time for another bakealong! I’ve teamed up with @tateandlylesugars to show you a delicious small batch recipe, a passion fruit and coconut cake, which is perfectly suited to right now. It also keeps really well so even if there is only a two of you in the house they’ll be no waste. Ingredients are listed below and the instructions are in the video. 
60ml coconut oil (or melted butter, veg or olive oil)
60ml yoghurt (or buttermilk, kefir, sour cream)
20ml passion fruit puree (or any citrus juice)
2 large eggs 
125g @tateandlylesugars pure cane caster sugar 
Zest of 2 lime (or any citrus)
60g self raising flour
50g ground almonds
50g desiccated coconut (or semolina)
1/2 tsp baking powder 
100g @tateandlylesugars icing sugar 
Pulp from 1-2 passion fruit (or citrus juice)

Finally! Im so excited that today I can finally share a sneak peek at my new book One Tin Bakes (released June 25th in the UK and AUS and Sept 1st in the US). When the book landed on my doorstep this morning I cannot tell how excited and happy I was, I love this book and I am so excited to see it on your book shelves and in your kitchens and to see you guys baking from it! The book uses just one tin, a 9x13 brownie tin and there are 70 recipes, including cakes, cookies and brownies, desserts and even a bread chapter. The recipes are varied and there is many fun ideas that I can't wait for you to explore. The skill level is wide so there is tons of recipes if you're a newbie and there is also plenty for the more seasoned bakers. I am just so excited for it to be out in the world!
If you are able to, and would like to, the book is available to pre-order wherever you are in the world and if you're going to buy it anyway preordering is a huge help (link is in my profile). It’s easy to preorder online but your local indie bookstore can also order a copy for you too #supportsmallbusiness 
I'm off to have a cocktail to celebrate 🎉🍸

node.text:
Its #plantmilkday so lets make an egg and dairy free butterscotch pudding using @alpro soya. Pudding, in this case, is the American style dessert a set custard, think a cross between angel delight and pastry cream.
100g light brown sugar
65g vegan butter
2 tsp vanilla bean paste
500ml @alpro soya original
30g cornflour
-
Add the sugar and butter to a saucepan and cook until melted and bubbling. Cook for a couple of minutes before removing from the heat and pouring in the soya and vanilla and place back on the heat and whisk until smooth and lump free. Pour a little of the soya mixture into a bowl with the cornflour and whisk to make a slurry. Pour this back into the pan and whisk to combine. Place over medium heat and cook, whisking constantly, until the mixture is thick and is bubbling. Remove from the pan and pour into the serving vessels, small glasses, champagne saucers, small bowls etc. Refrigerate until set and then top with a little vegan whipped cream and a sprinkling of pecan praline. #goodforyou #plantbased #pudding #veganbaking #vegandesserts #plantbasedfood #plantbaseddessert #theboywhobakes #butterscotch

Quick Tip
-
Most cookie doughs (especially those akin to a classic chocolate chip dough) freeze brilliantly. Make a batch, ball them up and then freeze them on a tray. When they’re frozen transfer them to a freezer bag or Tupperware (they won’t stick together this way) and the best part, you can bake them straight from frozen adding 1 or 2 minutes to the bake time! Whenever I have sourdough discard in the fridge I make a batch of these and freeze them because even if I’m not in the middle for a cookie right then, the time won’t be far away 😂
-

node.text:
Surely the ultimate labour of love, croissants! 
-
This is part 1 of the process and I’ll post the second half tomorrow. If only making a batch of croissant dough only took 60 seconds! I know they are tricky to make and are a significant time investment but I oddly really enjoy making them, makes the final product all the more rewarding when you make it yourself. Thankfully if you don’t want to make it we seem to be living in a golden age of croissants, but who makes your favourite? In London I love @aromebakerylondon @jolene_hackney @pophamsbakery @layla_w10 @flor.london @lbpedlar and so many more (I’m probably forgetting somewhere super obvious!)
-
